`crates/ctx-cage/` is the sandboxing crate for autonomous `claude` agent runs: it constrains filesystem, namespace, and network access while routing all outbound API traffic through a host-side proxy the caged process cannot bypass. Depending on this crate means a CLI (`ctx_cage`/`ctx_run`) that resolves flags into a validated `Mode`, executes a guaranteed prepare→run→teardown lifecycle via bwrap, and never exposes a real API key or agent-cmd config to the sandboxed process directly.

The crate has three top-level parts: `src/` (the implementation, its own rollup covers ADR-046 canonical-path and credential-isolation invariants), `assets/` (static files bind-mounted at cage setup — offline DNS stub and nsswitch config that must stay mutually consistent, plus an unrelated agent-doctrine prompt), and `tests/` (black-box validation of the public contracts, with no shared test infrastructure).

The DNS-hang failure mode (ADR-049) is the one invariant that spans directories: `assets/cage-resolv.conf`'s TEST-NET-1 nameserver, `src/lib.rs`'s compiled-in `CAGE_RESOLV_CONF` constant, and `tests/cage_assets.rs` + `tests/bwrap_build.rs` all must agree that DNS resolution fails fast rather than hanging — a change to any one requires checking the other three. Similarly, `assets/cage-rules.md` is compiled into `src/lib.rs` as `CAGE_RULES_MD`, so wording changes there change agent behavior without a src/ code change.

No `intent.md` exists for this directory or most of its subtree.

intent_divergence: no intent.md exists for this directory, so no divergence check is possible.